\begin_layout Subsection
Two Claims on Taxi Behaviors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "section_statistic_analysis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following two claims are foundations of the proposed taxi mobility model, which are also reasonable based on the experience in our daily life: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Claim 1:
\series default
 The behavior of a taxi changes when its status updates. When a taxi is occupied, its destination is certain, and the vehicular speed of a occupied taxi accelerates relatively. In contrast, when a taxi is vacant, it slows down or even stops to search for potential passengers along the road. Therefore, taxi behavior characteristics, such as speed and status duration, vary consequently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Claim 2:
\series default
 The movement behavior of taxis associates with geographic features. When a taxi is occupied, the destination may be tend to certain geographic places, such as the airport. Meanwhile, when a taxi is vacant, its driver tends to look for some hot spots, where more people want to take a taxi, such as downtown areas. Therefore, 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The destination selection of a taxi is influenced by different regions. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Events occur in different regions un-evenly, passenger drop and load events are distinct. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Claim 3:
\series default
 The movement behavior of taxis associates with time. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we analyze the speed, duration and passenger load/drop events distribution over the Beijing taxi traces to validate the two claims above.
\end_layout

